history.text: Hey
Hello!
SO, have you ever seen Toy Story?
Yes. I have. I think Pixar did an excellent job with the casting of this film.
Even the supporting characters are fantastically cast.
I think they did as well! I don't think I have ever seen a movie that had a 100% viewer rating!
That's a very good point! I wonder if the rating is nostalgia based, or if people would have given it a 100% rating in 1995
Yeah that is a good point actually about the nostalgia aspect!
I actually can't believe that movie came out in 1995
And Steve Jobs was the executive producer?!

I had no idea! Also, I didn
't know a Coen brother worked on the script!
Wow, compared to some of the extremely dark stuff that the Coen brothers work on in general. I had no clue.
So, do you have a favorite character in the movie?
I am tied between Slinky Dog, portrayed by Jim Varney and Don Rickles' Mr. Potato Head.
What about you?
I already really like Bo Peep,or Slinky Dog, who is played by Jim Varney
I love that they use baby monitors to communicate back and forth.
Agreed! It made the dramatic scene of learning about the gifts at the birthday party much more heightened. Like old fashioned radio.
Sid was terrifying on so many levels.
Yes exactly! There are so many little references like that throughout the film, I love it.
HAH! When I was a kid, Sid spooked me so much.
I love that Buzz is all "high tech" which increases the likeness between him and the other toys.
Exactly! That'
s a great point
And all of the other toys were so impressed by him
I know, hahaha just because he could press a button and open his wings.

I love the scene when they are at the p
izza place as well
But actually he served the same function as the other toys when it come down to it. Minus all the bells and whistles, he was still a regular toy, subject to the same insecurities
Me too! The crane game was a great nostalgic throwback
Oh yes definitely! There is a lot of undertones of bigger lessons throughout the film!
Some of the toys that Sid created were incredibly disturbing too
I think I remember that spider baby head thing
The ending was great. So many lessons, but friendship was the ultimate one
Also I forgot RC ran out of batteries. Such a real life trauma! ha ha
It really is! That small little RC car in the road hahah.
I think that was one of the best parts of the film. People could recognize so many of the toys and so many associated issues with them in their own lives (batteries, losing a toy, etc)
Also the idea of getting new toys during the holidays, but then always going back to the toys you knew and loved no matter what.
Oh that is right! The fear that they could possibly be replaced
Is it in the first film when Andy grows up in the end?
I'm not sure. I remember him getting the dog, and the other toes being worried about that, but I think the dog wouldn't replace the toys so much as maybe destroy them ha ha
Oh yes the dog, I remember the dog from the other films too!
I might actually watch this movie later on!

That had to be terrifying from a toy's perspective, especially
 after dealing with Sid's dog earlier!
It's such a classic film
I know I would be spooked if I saw another dog after Sid's intense dog!
And the damage that could be done to you!
Alright I think we've hit the amount of lines. Have a good day!
You too!
